        itineraire: "The journey from the 15th to CDG is one of the longest in Paris due to the arrondissement's southwestern position. From Beaugrenelle or the Front de Seine, the driver takes the Seine quays westward, joins the ring road at Porte de Sèvres, then heads up the western and northern ring road to Porte de la Chapelle. The A1 is then taken to CDG. From Porte de Versailles or Convention, the ring road is joined directly, then northward. From Rue de Vaugirard or the Pasteur quarter, the driver may opt for Boulevard Garibaldi then Les Invalides and the Seine quays northward. During peak hours, the ring road can be very busy between Porte de Sèvres and Porte de la Chapelle. The driver can then cross Paris internally via Boulevard des Invalides and Boulevard de Sébastopol. Allow 50 minutes under normal conditions, 65-70 minutes during busy periods.",
        conseils: "The 15th being Paris's largest arrondissement, journey time varies by quarter. From Beaugrenelle or Rue de la Convention, allow 50 minutes. From Porte de Versailles, 45 minutes. Allow 3h15 before an international flight. On trade show days at Porte de Versailles (check the calendar), traffic can be very heavy around Boulevard Victor and Boulevard Lefebvre. The driver knows alternative routes via interior streets. Front de Seine hotels have direct quay access. Rue du Commerce and Rue de la Convention, shopping streets, can be busy during market hours. Departures before 7am are fastest (40 minutes). Check your CDG terminal and tell the driver.",
